inference:
By the Angle Bisector Theorem,
\[\frac{AD}{DC} = \frac{AB}{BC} = \frac{17}{33}\]and
\[\frac{AE}{EB} = \frac{AC}{BC} = \frac{24}{33} = \frac{8}{11}.\][asy]
unitsize(0.6 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, I, M, N;

B = (0,0);
C = (33,0);
A = intersectionpoint(arc(B,17,0,180),arc(C,24,0,180));
D = extension(A,C,B,B + reflect(A,C)*(B));
E = extension(A,B,C,C + reflect(A,B)*(C));
I = extension(B,D,C,E);
M = extension(I,I + dir(180 - angle(A,I,B)),A,B);
N = extension(I,I + dir(180 - angle(A,I,C)),A,C);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(B--D);
draw(C--E);
draw(I--M);
draw(I--N);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$E$", E, S);
label("$I$", I, NE);
label("$M$", M, W);
label("$N$", N, E);
[/asy]

Since $MN \parallel BC,$ triangles $AMN$ and $ABC$ are similar.  Therefore,
\[\frac{AM}{AB} = \frac{AN}{AC} = \frac{MN}{BC}.\]Then
\[\frac{AM}{17} = \frac{AN}{24} = \frac{MN}{33}.\]Let $AM = 17x,$ $AN = 24x,$ and $MN = 33x.$  Then the perimeter of triangle $AMN$ is $17x + 24x + 33x = 74x.$

Also,
\[\frac{AD}{DC} = \frac{17}{33}\]implies $AD = 17k$ and $DC = 33k$ for some $k.$  Then $AC = AD + DC = 50k.$  Hence, $24x = 50k,$ so $x = \frac{25}{12} k.$

The perimeter of triangle $AMN$ is then $74x = 74 \cdot \frac{25}{12} k = \frac{925}{3} k.$

Since $k$ can be any positive real number, the perimeter of triangle $AMN$ can be any positive multiple of $\frac{925}{3}.$  Thus, we can take $k = \frac{3}{925},$ so the perimeter of triangle $AMN$ is $\boxed{1}.$

ground_truth:
Since $MN$ is parallel to $BC$, $\angle MIB = \angle IBC$.  But $BI$ is an angle bisector, so $\angle IBC = \angle IBM$.  Hence, triangle $MIB$ is isosceles with $MI = MB$.  By the same argument, triangle $NIC$ is isosceles, with $NI = NC$.

[asy]
import geometry;

unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, I, M, N;

A = (1,3);
B = (0,0);
C = (4,0);
I = incenter(A,B,C);
M = extension(I, I + B - C, A, B);
N = extension(I, I + B - C, A, C);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(B--I--C);
draw(M--N);

label("$A$", A, dir(90));
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$I$", I, dir(90));
label("$M$", M, NW);
label("$N$", N, NE);
[/asy]

Therefore, the perimeter of triangle $AMN$ is simply \begin{align*}
AM + AN + MN &= AM + AN + MI + NI \\
&= AM + AN + MB + NC \\
&= (AM + MB) + (AN + NC) \\
&= AB + AC \\
&= 17 + 24 \\
&= \boxed{41}.
\end{align*}

